    value: 悠
english:
  title: Memorial for the Dharma Assembly to Dispel Calamity
  author: Lee Kyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Treading upon mountains and emerging from the sea—behold the awesome form, radiant as thunder, wrapped in celestial power. Transmuting iron into gold—how wondrous the sacred incantations of the divine elixir. With undivided heart we bow and take refuge; the six arms embrace and sustain us. Yet I, humble and unworthy, have long soiled the weighty throne, my governance unable to attain the harmony of lute and zither. Blind to change and adaptation, the people drift into ravines and ditches with no salvation in sight. Order crumbles, chaos multiplies. Suddenly we are struck by calamities most severe, and granaries once teeming are utterly emptied. Ten thousand lives turned to cold ash in a single dawn—the wound festers still in my heart, leaving no peace even in sleep.

    Moreover, the heavens' observations show the stars astray from their proper courses. Mars enters the celestial guard's domain in retrograde motion; the moon shares lodging with the sun. What divine reproof is this? What catastrophe awaits?

    Though past disasters come as inevitably as the will of heaven, which we cannot escape, let us entreat the Buddha's power to avert the calamities yet to come. Here at the temple gate we knock, seeking the true sanctuary of enlightened protection. We establish the dharma assembly, the sacred circle of fragrant earth; reverently we unfold the sutras' jade scrolls and recite the secret teachings. As our devotion takes root and the Buddha's compassionate eye opens upon us, we humbly pray: May the five planets resume their rightful paths, the eight winds harmonize with the seasons, warfare cease its ravaging, and all households find peaceful rest. May the harvests flourish abundantly, swiftly replenishing our depleted granaries. May the barbarians abandon their treacherous designs, and may our nation's foundations endure for ages yet unborn.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six arms' refers to a six-armed bodhisattva, likely Avalokiteshvara, representing the multiple manifestations of compassion.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five planets' and 'eight winds' are traditional cosmic elements in East Asian cosmology, whose proper functioning ensures earthly harmony and prosperity.
  - key: ''
    value: This poem was likely written during a time of natural disaster and famine in Korea, with the author seeking Buddhist intervention to prevent future calamities.
